Who wants some actual food preservation hacks for those same items?
-Avocado: rub with lime juice, put in a plastic container in the fridge. Same result as the no-onion version, but less brown
-Egg yolks: Put the yolks in an ice cube tray, one to a compartment. If you need the trays after, just put 'em in a zip-top bag once they're thoroughly frozen. Thaw when needed. (You can do the same with the whites.) Salt eggs are a real thing, but they're not meant to preserve the eggs as eggs anymore than dill pickles are meant to be the same as cucumbers or kimchi is to be the same as fresh cabbage.
-Parsley (and other herbs): In water on the counter is pretty much the best way, but if you don't have the space, spread them out in a single layer on a length of damp paper towel, roll them all up, and put the roll in a plastic bag in the fridge. It'll last longer than if you just dump the herbs in the fridge straight from the store.
-Pineapple: If you're not using it yet, just leave it uncut in the fridge. If you've already cut it, instead of putting it upside down on a plate, finish cutting it and stick it in a zip-top bag in the freezer.
-Squash (those were butternut squash, btw): Best preserved whole, but if you've already cut one open, like you already found, plastic wrap over the cut part will keep them fresh a long time. Cubed, bagged, and frozen, they'll last for years.
So... Yeah, a lot of food preservation "hacks" come down to "stick it in the freezer." That's the whole reason they were invented.
